A construction project manager is responsible for overseeing the planning, implementation, and tracking of a specific short-term project. They are responsible for ensuring that the project is completed on time, within budget, and meets the quality standards set out in the project plan. Key roles and skills of a construction project manager include:
Planning and scheduling: The project manager must develop a detailed project plan that includes timelines, budgets, and resources required. They must also be able to identify and manage any potential risks to the project schedule and budget.
Budget management: The project manager must be able to create and manage a project budget, including the cost of materials, labor, and equipment. They must also be able to identify and manage any potential cost overruns.
Communication and leadership: The project manager must be able to effectively communicate with all stakeholders, including the project team, owner, and other contractors. They must also be able to lead and motivate the project team to achieve project goals.
Problem-solving: The project manager must be able to identify and solve problems that arise during the course of the project. They must be able to think creatively and critically to find solutions to unexpected challenges.
Technical knowledge: The project manager should have a good understanding of construction techniques, materials, and regulations to be able to oversee the work of other professionals.
Risk management: The project manager must identify, evaluate and mitigate risks that could impact the project schedule, cost, or quality. They must be able to anticipate and plan for potential problems before they occur.
Contract management: The project manager must be familiar with the terms and conditions of the contracts, and must be able to negotiate, execute and manage them.
Safety management: The project manager must ensure that safety standards and regulations are met throughout the project, and must be responsible for creating and maintaining a safe work environment.

A construction project manager must be able to balance multiple tasks and responsibilities and must have strong project management skills, leadership, and communication skills. It is also important that they have a good understanding of construction techniques, materials, and regulations. Additionally, being able to think critically and creatively, and having good problem-solving skills is crucial for a successful project manager.

